      • partition

        public static <E extends Comparable<E>> int partition​(List<E> a,
                                                      int pivot_idx,
                                                      int low,
                                                      int high)
        The element at index pivot_idx acts as a pivot. Rearranges a[low, high] and returns the new position new_pivot_idx of the original pivot element. In the rearranged array, all the elements smaller/larger than pivot appear before/after new_pivot_idx. Based on the Lomuto partitioning scheme https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/hoares-vs-lomuto-partition-scheme-quicksort/

      • binary_search_max

        public static int binary_search_max​(List<? extends State_Node> stage,
                                    int attr_index,
                                    double max_val,
                                    boolean inclusive)
        Binary search for the maximum element that is less than a max value on a stage of (T-)DP that corresponds to the tuples of a relation (i.e., @link{entities.paths.State_Node#state_info} is @link{entities.Tuple}). The attribute whose value we are searching for is specified by its index.
        Parameters:
        stage - The (sorted) list of nodes to be searched.
        attr_index - The index of the attributes that will be used for searching.
        max_val - The maximum value we are searching for.
        inclusive - Indicates whether we want values equal to max_val to be returned.
        Returns:
        The largest index whose value is less than (or equal to if inclusive) to the specified maximum value or -1 if no element satisfies the requirement.

      • split_by_distinct

        public static List<org.javatuples.Pair<List<? extends State_Node>,​List<? extends State_Node>>> split_by_distinct​(List<? extends State_Node> left,
                                                                                                                       List<? extends State_Node> right,
                                                                                                                       Join_Predicate inequality,
                                                                                                                       int no_partitions,
                                                                                                                       int max_values_per_partition)
        For 2 stages of (T-)DP that correspond to the tuples of relations, splits the left-right tuples into multiple partitions according to the inequality condition attributes. The left and right tuples have to be sorted beforehand and the number of distinct values has to be provided. The resulting partitions satisfy the following:
        • Each partition has about the same number of distinct values.
        • The partitions are sorted both locally and globally.
        The resulting list doesn't allocate new lists of nodes. Instead, views of the original list as sublists are used.
        Parameters:
        left - The first (sorted) subset of a relation/stage.
        right - The second (sorted) subset of a relation/stage.
        inequality - A single inequality predicate.
        no_partitions - The desired number of partitions.
        max_values_per_partition - The desired distinct values contained in each partition. Any remaining ones will be assigned to the last partition.
        Returns:
        List, List>> A partitioning of the nodes as a list of left-right pairs.

      • count_distinct_vals

        public static int count_distinct_vals​(List<? extends State_Node> stage1,
                                      List<? extends State_Node> stage2,
                                      int idx1,
                                      int idx2,
                                      double offset2)
        Given two stages of (T-)DP that correspond to relations, counts the number of distinct values of the tuples. The attributes whose values we want to count are specified by their indexes. We also allow a real number to be added as an offset to the values of one of the stages.
        Parameters:
        stage1 - The first stage.
        stage2 - The second stage.
        idx1 - The index of the attribute whose values we count for the first stage.
        idx2 - The index of the attribute whose values we count for the second stage.
        offset2 - An offset to be added to the values of the second stage.
